To verify that  $x \to x^3$  is one-to-one in the first two cases, notice that if  $x^3 = y^3$ , we may take the cube roots of both sides of the equation to obtain  $x = y$ . Clearly, the mapping from  $\mathbf{Z}$  to  $\mathbf{Z}$  given by  $x \to x^3$  is not onto, since 2 is the cube of no integer. However,  $x \to x^3$  defines an onto function from  $\mathbf{R}$  to  $\mathbf{R}$ , since every real number is the cube of its cube root (i.e.,  $\sqrt[3]{b} \to b$ ). The remaining verifications are left to the reader.

