In general, if  $\langle a\rangle$  has order  $n$  and  $k$  divides  $n$ , then  $\langle a^{n / k}\rangle$  is the unique subgroup of order  $k$ .

Taking the group in Theorem 4.3 to be  $Z_{n}$  and  $a$  to be 1, we obtain the following important special case.

# Corollary Subgroups of  $Z_{n}$

For each positive divisor  $k$  of  $n$ , the set  $\langle n / k \rangle$  is the unique subgroup of  $Z_{n}$  of order  $k$ ; moreover, these are the only subgroups of  $Z_{n}$ .

