Despite their relative scarcity among all finite groups up to large orders, finite Abelian groups are of fundamental importance in many branches of mathematics and have many applications.

In the following example the group is small enough that we can easily determine its isomorphism class from the orders of its elements.

EXAMPLE 1 Let  $G = \{1, 8, 12, 14, 18, 21, 27, 31, 34, 38, 44, 47, 51, 53, 57, 64\}$  under multiplication modulo 65. Since  $G$  has order 16, we know it is

isomorphic to one of

$$
\begin{array}{l} Z _ {1 6}, \\ Z _ {8} \oplus Z _ {2}, \\ Z _ {4} \oplus Z _ {4}, \\ Z _ {4} \oplus Z _ {2} \oplus Z _ {2}, \\ Z _ {2} \oplus Z _ {2} \oplus Z _ {2} \oplus Z _ {2}. \\ \end{array}
$$

To decide which one, we can use an online modular arithmetic calculator such as planetcalc.com/8326 to determine the orders of elements of  $G$ .

