# Georg Frobenius

Georg Frobenius combined results from the theory of algebraic equations, geometry, and number theory, which led him to the study of abstract groups, the representation theory of groups and the character theory of groups.

MacTudor

![](images/b392bdb6e0c6760e67c72e5e43c451f7bf3c0a8cc972ce4e7e0e511f0a692c9c.jpg)  
Courtesy of Oberwolfach Photo Collection

GEORG FROBENIUS was born in Berlin Prussia (now Germany) on October 26, 1849. He attended lectures by Kronecker, Kummer, and Weierstrass at the University of Berlin where he received his doctorate (awarded with distinction) in 1870 supervised by Weierstrass. In 1874, after having taught at secondary school level for a short period, he was appointed to the University of Berlin as an extraordinary professor of mathematics. The next year Frobenius received an ordinary professorship at the Eidgenössische Polytechnikum in Zürich, where he stayed for seventeen years. His pioneering work on representation theory for finite groups had important applications in quantum mechanics and theoretical physics.

Frobenius was the first to prove the Cayley-Hamilton theorem and gave the first abstract proof of the famous Sylow Theorem the says if  $p$  is prime and  $p^n$  divides the order of a finite group  $G$ , then  $G$  has a subgroup of order  $p^n$  (his proof is given in Chapter 23)

Frobenius was elected to the Prussian Academy of Sciences in 1892. He supervised 17 PhD students and has over 12,600 academic descendants. Wikipedia lists more than 35 things named after him.

Frobenius died August 3, 1917 in Berlin.

