# B. L. van der Waerden

This beautiful and eloquent text served to transform the graduate teaching of algebra, not only in Germany, but elsewhere in Europe and the United States.

SAUNDERS MAC LANE, Notices of the American Mathematical Society Vol.44, Number 3, 1997 321-322

![](images/4c4c4033359070a9f3ab5cfce44371f980a1aac81327b3150affba5cd3975f58.jpg)  
University of Evansville archive

B. L. van der Waerden was born on February 2, 1903, in Amsterdam, Netherlands. He studied mathematics at the University of Amsterdam and the University of Göttingen. At Göttingen, he attended lectures by Emil Artin (see Chapter 15 for a biography) and Emmy Noether (see Chapter 14 for a biography) on the abstract approach to ring theory being pioneered by Noether. The notes he took on these lectures became a two-volume book titled Moderne Algebra published in 1030-1931 that revolutionized the study of algebra that persists to this day.

After nearly 100 years, a translation of his algebra book is still in print. In a review of the book published in 1997 Sauders Mac Lane (see Chapter 16 for a biography) wrote "It [Moderne Algebra] is in my view, the most influential text in algebra of the twentieth century."

Beyond his classic book, van der Waerden made important contributions to the history of mathematics and science, and had more than 2300 academic descendants. van der Waerden died on January 12 1996 at age 92 in Zürich, Switzerland.

For more information on Van der Waerden, visit: https://mathhistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/\Biographies/Vander_Waerden/

