# The Cole Prize

Approximately every five years, beginning in 1928 (changed to every three years in 2003), the American Mathematical Society awards one or two Cole Prizes for research in algebra and one or two Cole Prizes for research in algebraic number theory. The prize was founded in honor of Frank Nelson Cole on the occasion of his retirement as secretary of the American Mathematical Society. In view of the fact that Cole was one of the first people interested in simple groups, it is interesting to note that no fewer than six recipients of the prize—Dickson, Chevalley, Brauer, Feit, Thompson, and Aschbacher—have

made fundamental contributions to simple group theory at some time in their careers. Recently the time between Cole Prizes was reduced to three years.

