# Classification of Finite Plane Symmetry Groups

Our first goal in this chapter is to classify all finite plane symmetry groups. As we have seen in earlier chapters, the dihedral group  $D_{n}$  is the plane symmetry group of a regular  $n$ -gon. (For convenience, call  $D_{2}$  the plane symmetry group of a nonsquare rectangle and  $D_{1}$  the plane symmetry group of the letter "V." In particular,  $D_{2} \approx Z_{2} \oplus Z_{2}$  and  $D_{1} \approx Z_{2}$ .) The cyclic groups  $Z_{n}$  are easily seen to be plane symmetry groups also. Figure 26.3 is an illustration

of an organism whose plane symmetry group consists of four rotations and is isomorphic to  $Z_{4}$ . The surprising fact is that the cyclic groups and dihedral groups are the only finite plane symmetry groups. The famous mathematician Hermann Weyl attributes the following theorem to Leonardo da Vinci (1452-1519).

